1. The post office wishes to issue a set of stamps   (integer denomination) so that with no more than 3 of them,   you can pay any postage from 1 cent to 70 cents. What   is the minimum number of stamps in the set?Looking at this a second time, I think I've managed to get it down to 8with the following combinations:1 2 3 7 11 26 41 56 (to 70)1 2 3 7 11 15 34 53 (to 71)1 2 3 4  9 14 33 52 (to 70)The way the stamps work is as follows:possibilities:1 ... n 2n+1 5n+3 8n+5 11n+7 14n+ 9 17n+11 20n+13 23n+15 26n+17 29n+19 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 7n+5 11n+8 15n+11 19n+14 23n+17 27n+20 31n+23 35n+26 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 4n+3  9n+7 14n+11 19n+15 24n+19 29n+23 34n+27 39n+31 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 4n+3  5n+4 11n+ 9 17n+14 23n+19 29n+24 35n+29 41n+34 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 4n+3  5n+4  6n+ 5 13n+11 20n+17 27n+23 34n+29 41n+35 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 4n+3  5n+4  6n+ 5  7n+ 6 15n+13 23n+20 31n+27 39n+34 ...1 ... n 2n+1 3n+2 4n+3  5n+4  6n+ 5  7n+ 6  8n+ 7 17n+15 26n+23 35n+31 ...best for n=1 is 10:1 3 5 7  9 20 31 42 53 64 1 3 5 7  9 11 24 37 50 631 3 5 7  9 11 13 28 43 58best for n=2 is 9:1 2 5 8 19 30 41 52 631 2 5 8 11 25 39 53 671 2 5 8 11 14 31 48 651 2 5 8 11 14 17 37 57best for n=3 is 8:1 2 3 7 11 26 41 561 2 3 7 11 15 34 53best for n=4 is 8:1 2 3 4  9 14 33 52best for n=5 is 9:1 2 3 4  5 11 28 45 621 2 3 4  5 11 17 40 631 2 3 4  5 11 17 23 52best for n=6 is 9:1 2 3 4  5  6 13 33 531 2 3 4  5  6 13 20 57best for n=7 is 10:1 2 3 4  5  6  7 15 38 611 2 3 4  5  6  7 15 23 54and n >= 8 can't do better than 8.From: rhoads@john.rutgers.edu (Glenn)>1)  If there are n stamps in the set, there are (n^2+5)n/6 ways to>select>    1, 2 or 3 of them.  For n=7, this value is 63, so at least 8 stamps>    are necessary.  So the above solutions (I'm assuming they're>correct)>    are optimal.>2)  If one is allowed to repeat denominations, then there are>    (n+1)(n+2)(n+3)/6 - 1 ways, which sets a lower bound of n=6 for any>    solution.This is the way I interpreted the problem.  There is a unique minimalsolution involving 7 stamps.The correct formula is C(n+2,3) = (n+2)(n+1)n/6n=7 yields 84. n=6 yields 56. so the formula gives 6 as a lower bound.On second thought, the non-repeating interpretation is better giventhe wording of the problem.  It's also harder to compute a solutionfor this version.  But it is neat that the other version has a uniqueoptimal set.  A better wording for the second version would be"...issue a set of denominations so that with no more than 3 stamps, ..."From: Bob Harris <nitlion@mindspring.com>Mythman wrote:> 1,3,8,12,18,22,31,57 satisfies 1..84> > This was done by hand so I apologize for any mistakes.This set satisfies 1..63,65..84.  No way to make 64.Interestingly, my by hand attempt last night (prior to seeing yours), isvery similar:1 3 8 12 22 28 48 54 statisfies 1..74Glenn's minimal set (which I have no reason to doubt)1 4 5 15 18 27 34 satisfies 1..70ObPuzzle:  What is the maximum range 1..n that can be satisfied by 8stamps?From: Jim Ferry <jferry@delete_this_field.uiuc.edu>-------- 2 stamps, 1 to 10 denominations --------  2,  2:   1  2,  4:   1  2  2,  4:   1  3  2,  8:   1  3  4  2, 12:   1  3  5  6  2, 16:   1  3  5  7  8  2, 20:   1  2  5  8  9 10  2, 20:   1  3  4  8  9 11  2, 20:   1  3  4  9 11 16  2, 20:   1  3  5  6 13 14  2, 20:   1  3  5  7  9 10  2, 26:   1  2  5  8 11 12 13  2, 26:   1  3  4  9 10 12 13  2, 26:   1  3  5  7  8 17 18  2, 32:   1  2  5  8 11 14 15 16  2, 32:   1  3  5  7  9 10 21 22  2, 40:   1  3  4  9 11 16 17 19 20  2, 46:   1  2  3  7 11 15 19 21 22 24  2, 46:   1  2  5  7 11 15 19 21 22 24-------- 3 stamps, 1 to 9 denominations ---------  3,  3:   1  3,  7:   1  3  3, 15:   1  4  5  3, 24:   1  4  7  8  3, 36:   1  4  6 14 15  3, 52:   1  3  7  9 19 24  3, 52:   1  4  6 14 17 29  3, 70:   1  4  5 15 18 27 34  3, 93:   1  3  6 10 24 26 39 41  3,121: