 current info knownabout this problem? e.g. approaches other than brute force?All messages from thread From: Adam Atkinson (ghira@mistral.co.uk) Subject: stamps problem (was Re: 5 Math Puzzles)  Newsgroups: rec.puzzles Date: 1998/10/10 On 08-Oct-98 08:56:33, Jim Ferry said:>-------- 2 stamps, 1 to 10 denominations --------etc.This "n stamps, k denominations" problem was discussed on a Rome BBSand in the pages of an Italian computer magazine within the last fewmonths. One of the readers produced a dazzlingly fast program whichproduced answers up to 3-4 stamps and somewhere-in-the-teensdenominations.What's a good source for more information on the current info knownabout this problem? e.g. approaches other than brute force?-- Adam Atkinson (ghira@mistral.co.uk)"Let's catch that sick bird" he said, illegally. From: Jim Ferry (jferry@delete_this_field.uiuc.edu) Subject: Re: stamps problem (was Re: 5 Math Puzzles)  Newsgroups: rec.puzzles Date: 1998/10/14 Adam Atkinson wrote:> > This "n stamps, k denominations" problem was discussed on a Rome BBS> and in the pages of an Italian computer magazine within the last few> months. One of the readers produced a dazzlingly fast program which> produced answers up to 3-4 stamps and somewhere-in-the-teens> denominations.> > What's a good source for more information on the current info known> about this problem? e.g. approaches other than brute force?Hi Adam,Do you know how high he was able to get for n=2, n=3 and n=4?My program has gotten to 17, 11 and 9 denominations respectively(I hope to coax it to 18, 12 or 13, and 10).Here are a few rather basic facts I've noticed:  1) The optimal solution for n=2 is:       j^2-2,   using {1,j},            for k=2j-3, (j=2,3,...)       j^2+j-2, using {1,j} or {1,j+1}  for k=2j-2, (j=2,3,...)  2)  A lower bound on the solution for k=2 is 4*(3*n-22):      there is a family of solutions defined for n >= 10      which yield this result (n < 10 can be checked as      special cases).  For n=14, the member of this family      is tied for optimal, for n=15, 16 or 17, the member      is the unique optimal solution.Note that for n=24, the value is $2.00.  The family member isquite unlikely to still be optimal for n=24, but it would makea nice problem:ObPuzzle:a)  Find 24 denominations such that one can make $.01 through    $2.00 with 2 stamps.  (Easy)b)  Can you get $.01 through $2.xx? (whatever the optimal value    here is).  (Hard)Now that I've O.P.'ed it, I guess I can't specify the family of"pretty good solutions."|             Jim Ferry              | Center for Simulation  | +------------------------------------+  of Advanced Rockets   || http://www.uiuc.edu/ph/www/jferry/ +------------------------+| jferry@expunge_this_field.uiuc.edu | University of Illinois |  From: Jim Ferry (jferry@delete_this_field.uiuc.edu) Subject: Re: stamps problem (was Re: 5 Math Puzzles)  Newsgroups: rec.puzzles Date: 1998/10/14 One more comment on the case of 2 stamps, n denominations:For all 1 <= n <= 17, with the exception of n=10, there isa (not necessarily unique) optimal solution that is "symmetric."If the optimally attained value is 2v, then a symmetric solutionis defined to have the following form:1, a1, a2, a3, . . ., v-a3, v-a2, v-a1, v-1, v.Therefore one could write a program to generate solutions whichare optimal among the symmetric solutions, thereby obtaining good,and very possibly optimal, solutions well above n=30.(Perhaps I'm beating a dead horse here . . .)|             Jim Ferry              | Center for Simulation  | +------------------------------------+  of Advanced Rockets   || http://www.uiuc.edu/ph/www/jferry/ +------------------------+| jferry@expunge_this_field.uiuc.edu | University of Illinois | From: QSCGZ (qscgz@aol.com) Subject: Re: stamps problem (was Re: 5 Math Puzzles)  Newsgroups: rec.puzzles Date: 1998/10/15 Jim Ferry wrote: >Ad